      ],
      "scripts": [
        {
          "number": 1,
          "script": "So far in this course, we have looked at how AI can support drug interaction checks and where it genuinely adds value. But now we need to have an honest conversation about where things can go wrong. Because the truth is, AI does not always get it right, and when it misses something in a clinical setting, the consequences can be serious. Sometimes the system misreads a combination of drugs and flags the wrong risk, or worse, flags nothing at all. Sometimes alerts are generated so frequently that clinicians start to ignore them, which is a real and well-documented problem. There are also situations where the underlying data the AI relies on is simply incomplete or out of date. And because these errors can be subtle, they often slip through without anyone noticing until harm has already occurred. In this lesson, we are going to explore each of these gaps in detail, so you can understand the risks and know what to watch out for."
        },
        {
          "number": 2,
          "script": "Before we explore how AI can help with drug interaction checks, we need to be honest about where it has fallen short. There have been real cases where AI systems failed to flag dangerous combinations of medications, and patients were seriously harmed as a result. In some instances, the alerts were there but were incomplete or so frequent that clinicians began to ignore them altogether. In other cases, the underlying drug databases simply had gaps, meaning the AI had no knowledge of certain interactions in the first place. And perhaps most concerning of all is the issue of overconfidence, where healthcare professionals trusted the AI output without questioning it, assuming the system had caught everything it needed to catch. These are not hypothetical risks. They are documented failures with serious consequences. So as we go through this course, it is important to keep this in mind: AI is a tool, and like any tool, it can be used well or poorly."
        },
        {
          "number": 3,
          "script": "So AI can be genuinely impressive at spotting drug interactions, but it does have real blind spots, and it's worth being honest about those. The biggest issue is that these tools are only as good as the data they were trained on. If that data is outdated, or if a particular drug combination is so rare it barely appeared in the training set, the AI simply won't flag it. The same applies to patients who don't fit the typical profile, perhaps someone with an unusual genetic makeup, or several overlapping conditions at once. Off-label prescribing is another area where AI tends to struggle, because it's working outside the boundaries of what it was taught. None of this means AI isn't useful, it absolutely is. But it does mean you can't hand over your clinical judgement to it. When the data is thin, your expertise and your knowledge of the individual patient in front of you still matter enormously."
        },
        {
          "number": 4,
          "script": "So we've established that AI can be genuinely useful for checking drug interactions, but it's not infallible, and this slide gets to the heart of why. The data these systems are trained on has real gaps, and those gaps can create genuine clinical risk. For instance, if a medication is rarely prescribed, there may simply not be enough data for the AI to flag a potential interaction accurately. Similarly, the training data might be outdated, meaning newer risks haven't been captured yet. If a drug is being used off-label, that use case may never have been included in the first place. Herbal remedies and supplements are another blind spot, often overlooked entirely despite being clinically relevant. And locally agreed formularies, the specific medicines your trust or organisation actually uses, are unlikely to feature in a generic AI system. So the message here is straightforward: AI is a support tool, not a safety net you can rely on completely."
        },
        {
          "number": 5,
          "script": "So AI can be genuinely impressive at spotting drug interactions, but it does have blind spots, and it's important we understand where those gaps can appear. These tools are only as good as the data they were trained on. If that data is outdated, or if it simply doesn't include newer medications or rare drug combinations, the AI may not flag a problem even when one exists. The same applies to patients who don't fit the typical profile, perhaps someone with an unusual genetic makeup, multiple overlapping conditions, or who is taking a medication for an off-label purpose. In those situations, the AI might stay completely silent, not because there's no risk, but because it hasn't seen enough similar cases to recognise one. And that silence can feel reassuring when it really shouldn't be. This is precisely why clinical judgement remains so important. AI is a useful tool, but it cannot replace the full picture that an experienced clinician holds."
        },
        {
          "number": 6,
          "script": "So we've seen what AI can do well, but let's be honest about where it struggles. One big issue is that AI systems are only as good as the data they were trained on, so newer or rarely prescribed drugs can slip through undetected. And if a patient's medical records are incomplete, the system simply cannot check what it doesn't know about. There's also a frustrating quirk where some tools will flag combinations that are actually quite low risk, while missing ones that are genuinely dangerous. When a patient is on five or more medications, the logic behind these alerts can really start to break down. On top of that, alerts often don't account for dosage, so the guidance feels too vague to be useful. Perhaps most critically, most systems have no awareness of how a patient's kidney or liver function might change how a drug behaves in their body. These are real, practical limitations that clinicians need to keep in mind."
        },
        {
          "number": 7,
          "script": "So let's talk about how AI is actually helping to reduce risk in practice. One of the most valuable things AI does is spot dangerous combinations of drugs before they ever reach the patient. Rather than waiting until after a prescription has been issued, these systems generate alerts at the point of dispensing, which means problems can be caught and addressed in real time. Now, we all know that human beings are brilliant, but we can miss things, especially under pressure or when dealing with a high volume of patients. AI helps to close those gaps. It can also identify rare interaction patterns that might not immediately come to mind, even for experienced clinicians. The result is that prescribers are better supported when making decisions, and patients are safer because of it. It is not about replacing professional judgement; it is about giving that judgement an extra layer of intelligent support."
        },
        {
          "number": 8,
          "script": "So let's bring everything together. The most important thing to hold onto is this: AI is a helpful tool, but it is not a safety net on its own. It can miss dangerous combinations, and it simply may not know everything about your patient, their age, their kidney function, their allergies. So always cross-check what the AI tells you against a trusted clinical source or a pharmacist. If something feels off, or you are not sure, escalate it. Do not sit on uncertainty. And if you do have concerns about advice an AI tool has given, write it in the patient record. That documentation matters. Now, for your next step, I would encourage you to try this in practice. Pick a medication you know well, run it through an AI tool, and then check the result manually. See where they agree, and more importantly, see where they do not. That hands-on experience will really help to build your confidence and your critical eye."
        }
      ]
